title: For Trade:  KLR-650 Off Road Bike for guns
postcontent: Dual sport 2006 Kawasaki KLR 650. I've had a blast on this, but haven't been able to ride it much since having kids, so it's time to go. I've added a bunch of stuff to it since purchasing and have it set up just how I like it. This bike is both trail and road ready....your choice.  First let me just say that these bikes are almost indestructible....almost. A small part deep within the bike, commonly called the "doohickey" (balance idle lever) is the only weak point on these machines.  One of the first things I did after purchasing, was swap that piece out and ensure that I wouldn't have an issue with it...which I haven't. So the "doohickey" work has been done. I've also added Tusk pannier racks to both sides and fixed lockable ammo cans (that I think add to the overall look of the bike, as well as act as armor in case of a drop) as pannier boxes. They are spacious, durable, and totally secure. They lock both to the rack and I have it set up so that the lid locks as well. I've also added a Top Box Quick Connect from Back Road Equipment to the rear of the bike and attached a Pellican 1550 box to the back. This allows me to remove the Pellican Box whenever I want (for instance if I'm travelling and my necessary items are in the box) without having to unbolt the box from the bike. This is also lockable. And for those that don't know about Pellican Boxes...do some research, they're the best. They're expensive, but worth it. So in summary, this thing is good to go. For an adventure bike, you simply can't do any better than this. Low miles, equipment already purchased and installed, and all the standard features and protective skid plating that comes with a KLR 650.

postcontent: The so called "Irish Contract" rifles are 1954 Fazakerley Arsenal - ones made in the serial range PF309348 to PF 359347.  Most were never delivered (more for the cost of rebarreling to [308] than any ‘political unrest’) and put in storage until sold as surplus.  This one has never been issued with all matching numbers.  Includes a new bayonette made the same year (the number is 333198).  Condition is 'as new' since it has never been issued.  There is a small import mark on the front right side of the barrel (as shown in one of the pictures).  This represents an excellent piece of enfield history!
